### Description

As far as I can tell, there isn't a way to cleanly nest components that contain inputs into a signals form. When nesting classes that implement `FormValueControl`, there doesn't seem to be a way to  pass the validation information to the nested components, especially if you access sub-components of the form value:

``` typescript
type Child = {
  a: number,
  b: number,
};
type FormContents = {
   first: Child,
   second: child
}

const childSchema  = schema<Child>((path) => {
  require(path.a);
});
```
If you apply the `childSchema` into a form that contains a form with the type `FormContents`, there doesn't seem to  be a good way to get to those error messages, especially if you wrote a `FormValueControl` component to abstract away entering a `Child` object.

### Proposed solution

I propose that a new interface, `FormGroupControl<T>`, and maybe a corresponding `formGroup` function be added that facilitates this use case. I'm not sure what the API would look like, but making the `formGroup` function similar to the current `form` function would make it easy to learn.

The idea would be to have the ability to use the `[formField]` directive in nested components to pass error messages down to  the nested components. This could be an opportunity to apply component-specific validation schemas, which would solve some of the validation issues.

Here's a rough example of what I've like to be able to do. 

``` typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-form-part',
  imports: [FormField],
  template: `
    <input type="number" [formField]="value.a">
    <input type="number" [formField]="value.b">
  `,
})
class FormPart implements FormGroupControl<Child> {
  public readonly value = model<Child>({
    a: '',
    b: '',
  });
  // maybe expose a formGroup method that functions similarly to `form` without
  // submission mechanics?
  public readonly group = formGroup(this.value, (schemaPath) => {
    // component-specific validation here?
    require(schemaPath.a);
    require(schemaPath.b);
  });
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-main-form',
  imports: [FormField],
  template: `
    <form>
      <app-form-part [formField]="form.first"/>
      <app-form-part [formField]="form.second" />
   </form>
  `,
})
class MainForm {
  formValue = model<FormContents>({...});
  form = form(this.formValue);
}

### Alternatives considered

I've tried the above example, except having `FormPart` implement `FormValueControl`, and there doesn't appear to be an easy way to associate the error objects with each form control, especially if you try to nest a `FormPart` within another `FormPart`.

Nesting form objects doesn't seem to be allowed. I don't think it would work anyways because you can't submit a sub-component of a form.

