core

### Description

A service declared with providedIn: 'root' is expected to behave as a singleton across the application.

However, if the same service is also included in providers at component or application level, multiple instances are created, effectively breaking the singleton behavior.

This leads to what appears to be a "loose singleton".

### Minimal reproduction

```ts
import { Component, Injectable, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';

let instances = 0;

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class Service {
  constructor() {
    instances++;
    console.log('Service:', instances);
  }
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-comp1',
  template: ``,
  providers: [Service],
})
export class Comp1 {
  service = inject(Service);
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-comp2',
  template: ``,
  providers: [Service],
})
export class Comp2 {
  service = inject(Service);
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <app-comp1 />
    <app-comp2 />
  `,
  imports: [Comp1, Comp2],
  providers: [Service],
})
export class App {
  service = inject(Service);
}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```

Current behavior
```
Service: 3
```

Each providers declaration creates a new instance, even though the service is marked as providedIn: 'root'.

### Proposed solution

A service with providedIn: 'root' should: Emit a warning / error when re-provided in providers

